WEBVTT

00:03.200 --> 00:06.260
- You think this was a copycat?
- I almost feel like he's
mocking her.

00:06.300 --> 00:08.734
Your name is Georgia Madchen.

00:08.770 --> 00:11.261
You're not alone.
Somebody told him

00:11.310 --> 00:14.473
we were coming.
- The man on the phone?
- Did you recognize his voice?

00:14.510 --> 00:16.705
- How much would I get
if you wrote a book about me?

00:16.750 --> 00:19.173
- Nicholas Boyle was gutted
with a hunting knife.

00:19.220 --> 00:21.176
You knew how to do that.
- You think I did this?

00:21.220 --> 00:23.438
- You and I are just gonna have
to have a difference of opinion

00:23.490 --> 00:25.617
about who Will is, Doctor.
- I'm worried about you, Will.

00:25.650 --> 00:28.289
What if you lose time and hurt
yourself? Or someone else?

00:28.320 --> 00:30.459
(gunshot)

00:42.240 --> 00:44.208
(ventilator pumping)

00:44.240 --> 00:46.231
(monitor beeping)

00:59.220 --> 01:01.085
(device beep)

01:03.360 --> 01:05.328
- You look better.

01:05.360 --> 01:09.797
- Do I look alive?

01:09.830 --> 01:13.163
- You look pretty.

01:15.840 --> 01:18.308
- Must be all the oxygen.

01:21.580 --> 01:23.571
They say what's wrong with you?

01:23.610 --> 01:26.670
- No, just the fever.

01:26.720 --> 01:29.143
They're trying to find out
what else.

01:29.190 --> 01:31.715
- They won't find anything.

01:31.750 --> 01:35.413
They'll keep looking,
keep taking tests,

01:35.460 --> 01:39.294
keep giving false diagnoses,
bad meds.

01:39.330 --> 01:42.197
But they won't find out
what's wrong.

01:44.200 --> 01:46.168
They'll just know

01:46.200 --> 01:48.566
that you're wrong.

01:48.600 --> 01:50.704
I hope you have good insurance.

01:50.740 --> 01:53.834
- I do too.

01:53.880 --> 01:57.202
- They're going to give me
shock treatment.

01:57.250 --> 02:01.311
Electroconvulsive therapy is
what it's called.

02:01.350 --> 02:04.786
Shock treatment sounds nicer.

02:04.820 --> 02:08.256
- People who have
what you have can
recover with shock treatment.

02:08.290 --> 02:11.259
- You know how many times
I've been told

02:11.290 --> 02:15.192
I could recover with treatment?

02:15.230 --> 02:18.358
They said I might remember
what I did.

02:20.900 --> 02:23.539
But I don't want to remember.

02:26.580 --> 02:29.299
- You know what you did,
Georgia.

02:31.310 --> 02:33.574
- But I don't remember it.

02:36.320 --> 02:38.288
It feels more like

02:38.320 --> 02:41.380
a horrible dream
where I killed my friend.

02:44.860 --> 02:47.749
- You dream about killing
anybody else?

02:47.800 --> 02:51.327
- I dream you killed
that doctor.

02:57.740 --> 03:01.278
But I couldn't see your face.

03:13.960 --> 03:15.780
- Smells delicious.

03:15.820 --> 03:19.449
- Silkie chicken in a broth.
A black-boned

03:19.500 --> 03:21.297
bird prized in China

03:21.330 --> 03:24.299
for its medicinal values
since the 7th century.

03:24.330 --> 03:27.936
Wolfberries, ginseng,
ginger, red dates,

03:27.970 --> 03:30.438
and star anise.

03:30.470 --> 03:33.701
- You made me chicken soup?

03:35.710 --> 03:37.439
- Yes.

03:42.850 --> 03:45.444
The nurses tell _me _
you've been wandering, WIll.

03:47.460 --> 03:50.952
- I was awake... heh...

03:50.990 --> 03:54.289
and wandering with... purpose

03:54.330 --> 03:56.469
and good intentions.

03:58.470 --> 04:00.836
- Visiting that unfortunate
young woman

04:00.870 --> 04:03.259
suffering from delusions.

04:03.310 --> 04:05.266
- She's my support group.

04:05.310 --> 04:07.528
- And I hope you're hers.

04:07.580 --> 04:09.969
Nothing more isolating
than mental illness.

04:22.430 --> 04:23.920
- The hallucinations,

04:23.960 --> 04:29.318
the, um, loss of time,
sleepwalking...

04:29.370 --> 04:32.760
could that have all just been
the fever?

04:32.800 --> 04:37.339
- Fevers can be symptoms
of dementia.

04:37.370 --> 04:40.430
Dementia can be a symptom
of many things happening

04:40.480 --> 04:43.472
in your body or mind that can
no longer be ignored, Will.

04:48.550 --> 04:50.347
- Does Jack know?

04:50.390 --> 04:53.689
- That this could be more than
a fever? No. I haven't told him.

04:53.720 --> 04:55.688
- Shouldn't you?

04:55.720 --> 04:57.722
- Not until we know
for certain.

05:00.860 --> 05:05.763
What we must do now is _continue
to support and monitor
your recovery.

05:05.800 --> 05:09.566
This young woman
you were visiting,

05:09.610 --> 05:12.101
how's her recovery?

05:12.140 --> 05:15.906
- I don't think she wants
to recover.

05:15.940 --> 05:18.704
Afraid to remember
what she did.

05:20.720 --> 05:22.711
- Can't say I blame her.

05:27.860 --> 05:30.829
(owgen flowing)

05:30.860 --> 05:32.851
(monitor beeping)

05:37.100 --> 05:39.466
(metallic thud)

06:08.860 --> 06:10.862
(zap)

06:21.480 --> 06:23.505
(no sound)

06:39.660 --> 06:42.959
***

07:24.010 --> 07:26.672
- The hospital speculates
that it was a short circuit

07:26.710 --> 07:29.770
that ignited the fire.
- Unit looks well maintained.

07:29.810 --> 07:31.801
No exposed wiring.

07:33.820 --> 07:35.776
- Horrible way to die.

07:35.820 --> 07:38.789
- There was a kid in Italy
who was in one of these things.

07:38.820 --> 07:41.983
A spark of static electricity
from his pajamas set it off.

07:42.020 --> 07:46.229
Two cubic yards of owgen
suddenly became two cubic
yards of fire.

07:46.260 --> 07:48.228
- Is it possible
that she set the fire herself?

07:48.260 --> 07:50.228
- She wasn't wearing
her grounding bracelet,

07:50.270 --> 07:52.966
which prevents the build-up
of static electricity.

07:53.000 --> 07:56.800
She took it off.
- Suicide by immolation?

07:56.840 --> 07:58.808
- She was facing
two murder charges.

07:58.840 --> 08:01.070
- She wasn't
suicidal, Jack.

08:01.110 --> 08:03.544
Sh-She was sick.

08:03.580 --> 08:06.003
I was here.
I spoke to her.

08:08.580 --> 08:11.686
- Why did you speak
with her?

08:11.720 --> 08:15.087
- Because I know
how she felt.

08:15.120 --> 08:18.089
- She's a murder suspect.
She tried to kill you.

08:18.130 --> 08:20.690
Your trying to be her friend
impacts the case against her.

08:20.730 --> 08:23.096
- Well, the case against her
doesn't really matter anymore,

08:23.130 --> 08:24.722
does it, Jack?

08:33.340 --> 08:36.309
- We could use the articles
I wrote at the time

08:36.340 --> 08:39.969
of each of the murders
as book chapter headings.

08:40.020 --> 08:43.239
The chapters themselves will be
you telling your story--

08:43.290 --> 08:46.316
where you were and what you were
thinking when, one by one,

08:46.350 --> 08:50.184
eight girls just like you
all over Minnesota were

08:50.230 --> 08:53.757
disappearing.
- What are we gonna call it?

08:53.800 --> 08:58.169
- I thought about
The Last Victim,

08:58.200 --> 09:02.239
but there is already a book
about serial killers called
The Last Victim.

09:02.270 --> 09:04.704
- Was it a bestseller?

09:04.740 --> 09:06.207
- Absolutely.

09:06.240 --> 09:09.004
Especially after the guy
who wrote it killed himself.

09:12.150 --> 09:13.845
- Just as well.

09:13.880 --> 09:17.043
Wasn't really my dad's
last victim anyway, was I?

09:21.720 --> 09:23.187
- Who was?

09:23.230 --> 09:25.949
- Marissa.

09:25.990 --> 09:30.120
- Marissa Schuur was killed
by the copycat.

09:30.170 --> 09:31.899
So was Cassie Boyle.

09:31.930 --> 09:34.239
- I still blame my dad.

09:36.240 --> 09:38.629
- Blame him
for Nick Boyle's death?

09:38.670 --> 09:43.039
- I blame Nick Boyle
for Nick Boyle's death.

09:43.080 --> 09:45.742
He killed Marissa.
He got what was coming to him.

09:45.780 --> 09:47.645
- Nick Boyle did not
kill your friend.

09:47.680 --> 09:49.113
- Then who did?

09:51.820 --> 09:54.812
- Better question is:
who killed Nick?

09:58.260 --> 10:01.252
Nick Boyle was
just a dumb kid

10:01.300 --> 10:06.260
who was really messed up
because his sister was murdered.

10:06.300 --> 10:09.030
He wasn't a killer.

10:09.070 --> 10:12.779
I've interviewed enough killers
to know one when I see one.

10:15.840 --> 10:17.842
- What gives them away?

10:20.950 --> 10:24.078
- A very specific brand
of hostility.

10:26.090 --> 10:29.355
I see it every time I look
at Will Graham.

10:29.390 --> 10:32.359
- He did kill my dad.

10:34.360 --> 10:36.897
- As far as I'm concerned,
he killed Nick Boyle.

10:36.930 --> 10:42.664
He and Jack Crawford told
everyone NIck was the copycat,

10:42.710 --> 10:45.361
and then someone murdered him
for It.

10:45.410 --> 10:48.937
- You really don't think
he did it.

10:51.310 --> 10:55.314
- Whoever killed Nicholas Boyle
killed an innocent man.

11:56.950 --> 11:58.941
- See?

12:03.990 --> 12:06.288
See?

12:31.410 --> 12:34.516
- What are you doing here?
- Checked myself out
of the hospital.

12:34.550 --> 12:36.984
- Well, check yourself back in.
- My fever broke.

12:37.020 --> 12:39.238
- I don't care.
- Georgia Madchen didn't

12:39.290 --> 12:42.851
commit suicide, and whatever
happened to her wasn't
an accident.

12:42.890 --> 12:45.427
- I'm gonna have Z come down
here and stick a thermometer

12:45.460 --> 12:49.055
in you, and if you've got
a temperature higher than 99--
- She was murdered, Jack.

12:52.170 --> 12:53.535
- By who?

12:53.570 --> 12:57.529
- By whoever killed
Dr. Sutcliffe.

12:57.570 --> 13:02.030
- His blood was all over
Georgia Madchen. Her DNA was

13:02.080 --> 13:04.048
all over him.
- She told me there was

13:04.080 --> 13:07.948
somebody else there.
She couldn't see his face.

13:07.980 --> 13:10.540
- There was somebody else there.
It was Dr. Sutcliffe.

13:10.590 --> 13:13.150
She couldn't see his face
because she cut it

13:13.190 --> 13:15.010
in half! Will,

13:15.060 --> 13:17.085
I understand. You're looking
for an explanation,

13:17.130 --> 13:19.155
an explanation
that makes all of this OK.

13:19.190 --> 13:21.897
- No! No, no, no. I don't.
That is not what I want. Listen,

13:21.930 --> 13:24.194
something went wrong, and
we will never know what that is,

13:24.230 --> 13:28.462
but for all the doctors she saw,
for all of the help
she received,

13:28.500 --> 13:30.559
she was ﬁghting
that wrong alone.

13:30.610 --> 13:32.566
- There is nothing you could do
about that.

13:32.610 --> 13:35.374
- All her adult life
this woman was misunderstood,

13:35.410 --> 13:36.968
And what I can do

13:37.010 --> 13:41.344
is make sure that her death
isn't misunderstood.

13:41.380 --> 13:44.588
She didn't kill herself.

13:44.620 --> 13:47.509
And this wasn't an accident.

13:52.490 --> 13:54.924
(heartbeat)

13:54.960 --> 13:57.963
(speaking indistinctly)

14:06.110 --> 14:09.534
- So, we dismantled
the oxygen chamber--see if
anyone tampered with the wiring,

14:09.580 --> 14:11.639
or even like a short circuit.
But nothing.

14:11.680 --> 14:13.216
- So what sparked the fire?

14:13.250 --> 14:14.615
- Inconclusive, but--

14:14.650 --> 14:18.484
- Not conclusively inconclusive.
Found this.

14:18.520 --> 14:20.954
Thought it might've been part of
the bed or monitoring equipment,

14:20.990 --> 14:23.959
but mass spectrometer said
it was celluloid plastic.

14:23.990 --> 14:25.958
They don't use plastic
in those things.

14:25.990 --> 14:28.629
- Right, right. It generates,
uh, static electricity.

14:28.660 --> 14:32.266
- Her_ hair_ was
melted right In there,
preserved like it was in amber.

14:36.400 --> 14:38.504
- Could it_ have been
a plastic comb?

14:38.540 --> 14:42.636
- Well, static charge from
a plastic comb in a highly
oxygenated environment

14:42.680 --> 14:46.104
would be a powerful accelerant.
- (Brian): Anything combustible
in there would combust.

14:46.150 --> 14:48.118
- You're holding
the murder weapon.

14:48.150 --> 14:50.687
- Or whatever she used
to kill herself, yeah?

14:50.720 --> 14:53.314
- Will--
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

14:53.360 --> 14:55.089
- Whoever killed Sutcliffe

14:55.120 --> 14:57.259
wanted to kill him
how Georgia Madchen

14:57.290 --> 15:01.090
killed her victim, but...
but not exactly how. Correct?

15:01.130 --> 15:04.293
- Georgia Madchen carved up
her victim's face.

15:04.330 --> 15:06.662
Sutcliffe was, uh, nearly
decapitated at the jaw.
I mean...

15:06.700 --> 15:08.668
- So she went further
the second time.

15:08.700 --> 15:11.703
Serial killers often do that.
- She was copied. Like, uh,

15:11.740 --> 15:15.278
whoever killed Marissa Schuur
and Cassie Boyle wanted to copy

15:15.310 --> 15:18.302
how Garret Jacob Hobbs killed
his victims.

15:25.590 --> 15:28.457
But not exactly how.

15:28.490 --> 15:30.651
- Wait a minute.
Are you sayIng

15:30.690 --> 15:35.298
that Dr. Sutcliffe was killed
by Garret Jacob Hobbs' copycat?

15:38.530 --> 15:41.067
- So was Georgia Madchen.

15:43.210 --> 15:45.701
Because he thinks
she saw his face.

15:45.740 --> 15:48.004
- You said Nicholas Boyle was
the copycat.

15:48.040 --> 15:51.407
His blood was
on one of the victims.
Nicholas Boyle is dead.

15:51.450 --> 15:54.749
- Well, then he isn't
the copycat.

15:54.780 --> 15:58.181
- Could_ this be more
than just a fever?

15:58.220 --> 16:01.678
Will is connecting murders that
previously had no connections.

16:01.720 --> 16:03.278
- Beyond his involvement

16:03.330 --> 16:06.049
in the investigations?
- That's right.

16:06.090 --> 16:09.423
- So you're wondering
if the lines are blurring,
or if he's on to something.

16:09.460 --> 16:11.462
- I'm wondering
all sorts of things.

16:14.640 --> 16:17.609
What's Will's relationship
with Abigail Hobbs right now?

16:23.350 --> 16:25.705
- You think he's protecting her.
- He has been

16:25.750 --> 16:29.345
ever since he shot her father.
I just don't know from what.

16:29.380 --> 16:32.247
- I can't imagine he would hide
anything criminal from you.

16:32.290 --> 16:36.056
I've only ever known Will
as a man striving to be
his best self.

16:36.090 --> 16:39.480
- You haven't known him
that long.

16:39.530 --> 16:42.192
But we both know him well enough
to know he hasn't been himself.

16:42.230 --> 16:45.461
- He needs our support,

16:45.500 --> 16:48.697
whether or _not
mental Illness IS Involved.

16:48.740 --> 16:52.437
- Mental illness...

16:52.470 --> 16:54.574
Is it really mental illness,
Doctor, or is it just that

16:54.610 --> 16:57.044
his mind works so differently
from most people's

16:57.080 --> 16:59.548
that we don't know
what else to call it?

17:01.750 --> 17:05.208
- There are days
when even Will doesn't
understand his own thinking.

17:08.520 --> 17:10.522
(knocking on door)

17:12.790 --> 17:14.348
- Dr. DuMaurier.

17:14.400 --> 17:16.595
I'm Special Agent Jack Crawford
with the FBI.

17:16.630 --> 17:19.360
I'd like to talk with you
about a patient of yours.

17:25.570 --> 17:28.334
(music playing)
- Do you have a court order?

17:28.380 --> 17:30.348
- Well, I'd rather not get one

17:30.380 --> 17:32.746
if I don't have to.
(mu5Ic turned off)

17:32.780 --> 17:35.340
- So _it's_ not_
an offICIal IanIry.

17:35.380 --> 17:36.847
- Not yet.

17:36.880 --> 17:39.144
I'd hate to damage
anyone's reputation

17:39.190 --> 17:41.158
unnecessarily.

17:41.190 --> 17:43.750
- Whose reputation would
that be?

17:43.790 --> 17:46.327
- I suspect that Dr. Hannibal

17:46.360 --> 17:48.499
Lecter may be withholding
pertinent information

17:48.530 --> 17:52.296
involving a murder
investigation.

17:52.330 --> 17:55.367
No, thank you.

17:55.400 --> 17:59.530
- So... he hasn't confided
in the FBI.

17:59.570 --> 18:03.609
You are hoping he's confided
in his psychiatrist

18:03.650 --> 18:05.675
and that I'll tell you.

18:05.710 --> 18:07.439
- Yes, ma'am.

18:09.450 --> 18:11.680
It's not that I think
Dr. Lecter's dangerous. I don't.

18:11.720 --> 18:14.689
I am concerned
about a relationship he has

18:14.720 --> 18:16.813
with one of his patients,
a man named Will Graham.

18:16.860 --> 18:20.159
- Without consent
or a court order,

18:20.200 --> 18:22.725
I'd be in breach
of confidentiality.

18:22.760 --> 18:25.558
- That's correct.

18:25.600 --> 18:27.898
So, if we can't discuss
Dr. Lecter,

18:27.940 --> 18:30.602
perhaps we can discuss you.

18:30.640 --> 18:34.906
You were attacked by a patient
not too long ago.

18:34.940 --> 18:36.908
I read the report.

18:36.940 --> 18:40.444
I know that there was
a statement gIven by Dr. Lecter.

18:40.480 --> 18:43.608
- The patient who attacked me

18:43.650 --> 18:46.915
was a former patient
of Dr. Lecter.

18:46.950 --> 18:49.657
- And he was referred to you
by Dr. Lecter?

18:49.690 --> 18:52.682
- Yes.
- And this patient
almost killed you.

18:54.700 --> 18:57.863
- He swallowed his tongue
while he was attacking me.

18:57.900 --> 19:00.539
That's the only thing
that saved my life.

19:00.570 --> 19:04.301
- Well, thank God
for small favors.

19:04.340 --> 19:06.501
- Yes, thank God.

19:09.380 --> 19:11.473
- You should know there was
another attack recently

19:11.510 --> 19:14.741
in Dr. Lecter's office.
It involved another patient.

19:14.780 --> 19:17.817
Two dead, including the patient.

19:17.850 --> 19:22.549
- That's not bad psychology,
Agent Crawford.

19:22.590 --> 19:25.229
Putting me in a position
to have to defend

19:25.260 --> 19:27.797
or not to defend Dr. Lecter.
- You have to admit

19:27.830 --> 19:30.822
he's had some pretty strange
relationships with some
of his patients.

19:32.830 --> 19:36.766
- Complicated patients are
conducive to complicated
relationships.

19:36.800 --> 19:38.700
- All right.

19:38.740 --> 19:41.777
How far do you think

19:41.810 --> 19:45.701
Dr. Lecter would go
in his therapy to treat
a patient? Specifically,

19:45.750 --> 19:47.513
Will Graham.

19:47.550 --> 19:51.611
- Hannibal refers
to Will Graham

19:51.650 --> 19:55.313
more as a friend
than as a patIent.

19:55.360 --> 19:59.456
- How far do you think
he would go to treat a friend?

19:59.490 --> 20:01.856
- Well, he doesn't have
many of them,

20:01.900 --> 20:05.461
so I imagine
he'd be loyal.

20:05.500 --> 20:08.867
I know that he's concerned
about Will Graham

20:08.900 --> 20:12.768
and I know that he wants
to help him.

20:12.810 --> 20:15.836
- Well, I consider Will
a friend,

20:15.880 --> 20:18.348
and I'd like
to help him too.

20:18.380 --> 20:21.611
- It seems to me
that Will Graham would do well

20:21.650 --> 20:23.743
to have more friends like

20:23.790 --> 20:25.985
Dr. Lecter.

20:33.500 --> 20:35.991
- Will Graham theorized
that the copycat killer

20:36.030 --> 20:39.761
and Garret Jacob Hobbs were
somehow connected--

20:39.800 --> 20:41.768
that he had insight

20:41.800 --> 20:44.360
into Hobbs' personal life,
that they may have met,

20:44.410 --> 20:46.765
known each other,
perhaps even killed together.

20:46.810 --> 20:49.779
- See, I would call that less of
a theory, more of a hypothesis.

20:49.810 --> 20:52.370
- Hm, theories require evidence.
- Hm.

20:52.410 --> 20:55.777
- Let's play Jeopardy, shall we?
The answer is that

20:55.820 --> 20:58.345
these people were killed
by the copycat, who's connected

20:58.390 --> 21:00.381
to Garret Jacob Hobbs.
You tell me how.

21:00.420 --> 21:02.388
- You mean beyond
the application

21:02.420 --> 21:04.388
of supposition
and unexplained leaps?

21:04.430 --> 21:06.955
- Yes, that's right.
- I've been yearning

21:06.990 --> 21:09.322
for a return to the fundamentals
of Investigation.

21:09.360 --> 21:10.793
- Right?

21:10.830 --> 21:12.798
- Where is Beverly?

21:12.830 --> 21:15.936
- Jury duty.
- It's... She's
deposed in court.

21:15.970 --> 21:19.428
- Get her out of court.
Then here's what we're gonna do.

21:19.470 --> 21:23.941
I wanna look at train station,
airport, toll road,
hotel details.

21:23.980 --> 21:28.019
I wanna track Garret Jacob Hobbs
usmg lIcense plate capture
from security footage.

21:28.050 --> 21:32.680
I also want to know
every phone call he made
and where he made them from.

